these two books and the words that filled them were the balm I didnâ€™t know I need or could have. 

how seen i felt with every turn of page.

how soothing it was to have some of my deepest and hidden emotions brought forward and articulated in ways i never would have had the capacity.

and it genuinely felt like Brand was conversing with Lorde as I read these two back to back... it just made the experience all the more great.

iâ€™m currently reading Tessa McWattâ€™s Shame on Me and she used the word â€˜continuityâ€™ to describe what she sought out of her ancestry.

McWattâ€™s use of the word Continuity really helped me frame what I loved so much about A Map to the Door of No Return and Sister Outsider because they explored that desireâ€”that lackâ€”and challenged its necessity to us as Black people, particularly Black women, in the diaspora. How easily this desire has mutated and been exploited as a means to uphold the institutions and systems that destroy us. As Lorde famously said, â€œthe masterâ€™s tools will never dismantle the masterâ€™s house.â€ 

all this to say, 1000000000000000/10 recommending these two, i will be revisiting them often. McWattâ€™s Shame on Me is also pretty great (in a â€œin my light skin feelsâ€ type of way, i will not lie ğŸ˜‚)
 
